  "prompt": "Why do VR headsets cost so much when you can buy a phone with similar features for less than quarter of the cost?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why VR headsets tend to be more expensive than smartphones:\n\n1. Specialized Hardware\n- High-resolution displays with high refresh rates\n- Advanced motion tracking sensors\n- Precision optics and lens systems\n- Specialized graphics processing capabilities\n\n2. Lower Production Volume\n- Smartphones are mass-produced in millions\n- VR headsets have much smaller production runs\n- Lower volume means higher per-unit manufacturing costs\n\n3. Complex Engineering\n- Precise screen calibration\n- Advanced motion tracking technology\n- Intricate lens and display alignment\n- More complex design requirements\n\n4. Research and Development\n- Cutting-edge technology\n- Significant investment in developing new technologies\n- Relatively new market with high R&D costs\n\n5. Niche Market\n- Smaller consumer base compared to smartphones\n- Less competition keeps prices higher\n- Specialized components are more expensive\n\n6. Additional Components\n- Often include controllers\n- Require more sophisticated internal computing systems\n- More robust build quality for comfortable wearing\n\n7. Performance Requirements\n- Need to render complex 3D graphics in real-time\n- Require high computational power\n- Must maintain low latency for user experience\n\nWhile prices are gradually decreasing as technology improves and production scales up, these factors currently contribute to VR headsets' higher cost compared to smartphones.",
